@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xv) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a DURATION literal (`5s`). eval folds a duration to its
-- millisecond count as a plain Number (so `5s` displays `5000`); `lowerLit` in the
-- compiler still refuses the duration literal (§11.3 says it erases to `Num(ms)`, but the
-- fold is not yet wired). The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN
-- refusal at the compiler frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals (`$atom`-tagged, interned; see compile_atom_test). The frontier
-- now sits at DURATION literals. This file uses one, so it still refuses; when durations
-- lower (a later D1 slice, folding `5s` → `5000`), it flips from `unsupported` to a print.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let d = 5s
  println(d)
